  "statement": "# Spiral Matrix\n\nReturn all matrix values in clockwise spiral order.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: matrix = [[1,2,3],[4,5,6],[7,8,9]]\nOutput: [1,2,3,6,9,8,7,4,5]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: matrix = [[1,2,3,4]]\nOutput: [1,2,3,4]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: matrix = [[1],[2],[3]]\nOutput: [1,2,3]\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Inputs are sized for local offline execution.\n- Return the value described by the method signature.",
  "editorial": "Use direct arithmetic, matrix indexing, or bit operations to preserve the required invariants while keeping extra state small.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def spiralOrder(self, matrix):\n        out = []\n        top, bottom, left, right = 0, len(matrix) - 1, 0, len(matrix[0]) - 1\n        while top <= bottom and left <= right:\n            out += matrix[top][left:right + 1]; top += 1\n            for r in range(top, bottom + 1): out.append(matrix[r][right])\n            right -= 1\n            if top <= bottom: out += matrix[bottom][left:right + 1][::-1]; bottom -= 1\n            if left <= right:\n                for r in range(bottom, top - 1, -1): out.append(matrix[r][left])\n                left += 1\n        return out\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Watch fixed-width integer boundaries where the prompt requires them.",
    "For matrix mutation, mark or capture affected rows and columns before overwriting."
  ],
